{"title_page": "Paul F. Knitter", "text_new": "{{Infobox academic\n| name               = Paul F. Knitter\n| image              = Paulknitter.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Paul Francis Knitter\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1939|02|25}}\n| birth_place        = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], US\n| death_date         = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| residence          = \n| spouse             = Cathy Cornell ({{abbr|m.|married}}&nbsp;{{circa|1984}})<ref>{{cite book |last=Knitter |first=Paul F. |year=2009 |title=Without Buddha I Could Not Be a Christian |location=London |publisher=Oneworld |publication-date=2013 |page=xvi |isbn=978-1-78074-248-9}}</ref>\n| children           = \n| parents            =\n| awards             = <!--notable national level awards only-->\n| alma_mater         = {{unbulleted list | [[Pontifical Gregorian University]] | [[University of Marburg]]}}\n| thesis_title       = \n| thesis_url         = \n| thesis_year        = \n| school_tradition   = \n| doctoral_advisor   = \n| academic_advisors  = \n| influences         = <!--must be referenced from a third party source-->\n| era                = \n| discipline         = Theology\n| sub_discipline     = <!--academic discipline specialist area \u2013 e.g. Sub-atomic research, 20th Century Danish specialist, Pauline research, Arcadian and Ugaritic specialist-->\n| workplaces         = {{unbulleted list | [[Xavier University]] | [[Union Theological Seminary (New York City)|Union Theological Seminary]]}}\n| doctoral_students  = <!--only those with WP articles-->\n| notable_students   = <!--only those with WP articles-->\n| main_interests     = [[Religious pluralism]]\n| notable_works      = \n| notable_ideas      = \n| influenced         = <!--must be referenced from a third party source-->\n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n}}\n'''Paul Francis Knitter''' (born 1939) was the Paul Tillich Professor of Theology, World Religions and Culture at [[Union Theological Seminary (New York City)|Union Theological Seminary, New York City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.utsnyc.edu/Page.aspx?pid=381|title=Paul F. Knitter|publisher=Union Theological Seminary|accessdate=January 20, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100105141742/http://www.utsnyc.edu/Page.aspx?pid=381|archivedate=January 5, 2010}}</ref> He continues as the Emeritus Professor of Theology, World Religions and Culture.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://utsnyc.edu/academics/faculty/emeritus/ |title=Faculty Emeriti/ae|publisher=Union Theological Seminary|accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref> He was formerly Emeritus Professor of Theology at [[Xavier University]] in [[Cincinnati]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quaker.org/ftc/PaulKnitterBio.html|title=Paul F. Knitter Biographical Summary|publisher=Friends Theological College|accessdate=20 January 2010}}</ref> Since publishing his book, ''No Other Name?'' (1985), Knitter has been widely known for his [[religious pluralism]].  Along with his friend and colleague, the Protestant philosopher of religion [[John Hick]], Knitter came under criticism from Cardinal [[Joseph Ratzinger]], later known as Pope Benedict XVI.\n\nIn 1984 he was one of 97 theologians and religious persons who signed [[A Catholic Statement on Pluralism and Abortion]], calling for pluralism and discussion within the [[Catholic Church]] regarding the [[Catholic Church and abortion|church's position on abortion]].<ref name=\"Keller et al\">{{cite book |first1=Rosemary Skinner |last1=Keller |first2=Rosemary Radford |last2=Ruether |first3=Marie |last3=Cantlon |title=Encyclopedia of Women and Religion in North America |volume=3 |publisher=Indiana University Press |year=2006 |isbn=978-0-253-34688-9 |pages=1104\u20131106}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nKnitter was born on February 25, 1939, in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]. He holds a licentiate from the [[Pontifical Gregorian University]] in Rome (1966), as well as a doctorate from the [[University of Marburg]], Germany (1972).\n\n==Works==\n===Thesis===\n*{{cite thesis |author1-last=Knitter |author1-first=Paul F. |author1-mask= |title=Towards a Protestant Theology of Religions |series=Marburger Theologische Studien |volume=11 |type=PhD |location=Marburg |publisher=N.G. Elwert |date=1974 |ISBN=9783770804856 |OCLC=611481104 }}\n\n===Books===\n*{{cite book |author1-last=Knitter |author1-first=Paul F. |author1-mask=3 |title=No Other Name? A Critical Survey of Christian Attitudes toward World Religions |series=American Society of Missiology series |volume=7 |location=Maryknoll, NY |publisher=Orbis Books |date=1985 |ISBN=9780883443477 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/noothernamecriti00knit }}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Knitter |editor1-first=Paul F. |editor1-mask=3 |editor2-last=Hick |editor2-first=John |editor2-link=John Hick |title=The Myth of Christian Uniqueness: Toward a Pluralistic Theology of Religions |url=https://archive.org/details/mythofchristianu00hick |url-access=registration |location=Maryknoll, NY |publisher=Orbis Books |date=1987 }}\n*{{cite book |author1-last=Knitter |author1-first=Paul F. |author1-mask=3 |author2-last=Hill |author2-first=Brennan |author2-link=Brennan Hill |author3-last=Madges |author3-first=William |author3-link=William Madges |title=Faith, Religion, and Theology: A Contemporary Introduction |location= |publisher=Twenty-Third Publications |date= 1989 }}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Knitter |editor1-first=Paul F. |editor1-mask=3 |editor2-last=Corless |editor2-first=Roger |editor2-link=Roger Corless |title=Buddhist Emptiness and Christian Trinity Essays and Explorations |location=Mahwah, NJ |publisher=Paulist Press |date=1990 |ISBN=9780809131310 }}\n*{{cite book |author1-last=Knitter |author1-first=Paul F. |author1-mask=3 |author2-last=Cobb, Jr. |author2-first=John B. |author2-link=John B. Cobb, Jr. |author3-last=Hellwig |author3-first=Monika |author3-link=Monika Hellwig |author4-last=Swidler |author4-first=Leonard |author4-link=Leonard Swidler |title=Death or Dialogue: From the Age of Monologue to the Age of Dialogue |location=London |publisher=SCM Press |date=1990 |ISBN=9780334024453 }}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Knitter |editor1-first=Paul F. |editor1-mask=3 |title=Pluralism and Oppression: Theology in World Perspective |series=Annual publication of the College Theology Society |volume=34 |location=Lanham |publisher=University Press of America |date=1990 |ISBN=9780819179043 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/pluralismoppress0000pani }}\n*{{cite book |author1-last=Knitter |author1-first=Paul F. |author1-mask=3 |title=One Earth Many Religions: Multifaith Dialogue and Global Responsibility |location=Maryknoll, NY |publisher=Orbis Books |date=1995 |ISBN=9781570750373 }}\n*{{cite book |author1-last=Knitter |author1-first=Paul F. |author1-mask=3 |title=Jesus and the Other Names: Christian Mission and Global Responsibility |location=Maryknoll, NY |publisher=Orbis Books |date=1996 |ISBN=9781570750533 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/jesusothernamesc0000knit }}\n*{{cite book |author1-last=Knitter |author1-first=Paul F. |author1-mask=3 |editor1-last=Swidler |editor1-first=Leonard |editor1-link=Leonard Swidler |editor2-last=Mojzes |editor2-first=Paul |editor2-link=Paul Mojzes |title=The Uniqueness of Jesus: A Dialogue with Paul Knitter |location=Maryknoll, NY |publisher=Orbis Books |date=1997 |ISBN=9781570751233 }}\n*{{cite book |author1-last=Knitter |author1-first=Paul F. |author1-mask=3 |title=Introducing Theologies of Religions |location=Maryknoll, NY |publisher=Orbis Books |date=2002 |ISBN=9781570754197 }}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Knitter |editor1-first=Paul F. |editor1-mask=3 |editor2-last=Muzaffar |editor2-first=Chandra |editor2-link=Chandra Muzaffar |title=Subverting Greed: Religious Perspectives on the Global Economy |location=Maryknoll, NY |publisher=Orbis Books |date=2002 |ISBN=9781570754463 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/subvertinggreedr2002unse }}\n*{{cite book |author1-last=Knitter |author1-first=Paul F. |author1-mask=3 |title=The Myth of Religious Superiority: multifaith explorations of religious pluralism |location=Maryknoll, NY |publisher=Orbis Books |date=2005 |ISBN=9781570756276 }}\n*{{cite book |author1-last=Knitter |author1-first=Paul F. |author1-mask=3 |title=Without Buddha I Could Not Be a Christian |location=Oxford |publisher=Oneworld |date=2009 |ISBN=9781851686735 }}\n\n===Critiques from within Paul Knitter's native Catholic tradition===\nIn reference to Paul Knitter's ''Jesus and the Other Names'' (Maryknoll, N.Y.: Orbis, 1996), [[Catherine Cornille]], when addressing Knitter's claim that Jesus is not the \"only\" savior, comments: \"Not only are the religious views of different traditions at times directly opposed or mutually exclusive, but the very claim of ultimacy of one religion necessarily precludes the truth of the claims of others.\"<ref>Catherine Cornille, ''The im-Possibility of Interreligious Dialogue'', New York, NY: Crossroad Publishing, 2008, p.87.</ref> \n\nIn reference to Knitter's ''Without Buddha I Could Not Be a Christian'' (Oxford: Oneworld Publications, 2009), [Rev.] James L. Fredericks declares: \"Nowhere are we given to believe that there are some respects in which Buddhists and Christians are simply baffling to one another because their religious visions are incompatible. I also worry that the more Buddhism is enlisted into service of Christian faith as an ''ancilla theologiae'' [handmaid to theology], the less it seems like Buddhism.\"<ref>J. Fredericks' pertaining review entitled \"The Lotus Position,\" ''Commonweal Magazine'', April 5th, 2010.</ref>\n\nIn reference to ''Without Buddha I Could Not Be a Christian'', [[Robert Magliola]] asserts, in the ''Journal of the American Academy of Religion'' (''JAAR'')<ref>R. Magliola's pertaining review in ''JAAR'', Vol. 78, No. 4 (Dec., 2010), pp. 1215-1218.</ref> that Paul Knitter \"is not Catholic enough because he is not Buddhist enough and vice versa.\" Quoting [Rev.] Francis X. Clooney, S.J.'s assertion, in Clooney's ''Jesuit Postmodern'' (2006, p. 165) that comparisons \"seem not to fit into a single, coherent view,\" Magliola points out that Knitter's proposed \"one universal Spirit\" perpetuates the outdated modernist notion of \"equable holism\" or \"openness\" (the \"modern idol\") rather than the \"jagged, asymmetrical\" nature of reality.<ref>P. 1218.</ref>   \n\n\n\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Religion}}\n* [[Wilfred Cantwell Smith]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Union Theological Seminary (New York City)}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knitter, Paul F.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pontifical Gregorian University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Marburg alumni]]\n[[Category:Union Theological Seminary (New York City) faculty]]\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:People from Chicago]]\n\n\n{{US-theologian-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox academic\n| name               = Paul F. Knitter\n| image              = Paulknitter.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Paul Francis Knitter\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1939|02|25}}\n| birth_place        = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], US\n| death_date         = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| residence          = \n| spouse             = Cathy Cornell ({{abbr|m.|married}}&nbsp;{{circa|1984}})<ref>{{cite book |last=Knitter |first=Paul F. |year=2009 |title=Without Buddha I Could Not Be a Christian |location=London |publisher=Oneworld |publication-date=2013 |page=xvi |isbn=978-1-78074-248-9}}</ref>\n| children           = \n| parents            =\n| awards             = <!--notable national level awards only-->\n| alma_mater         = {{unbulleted list | [[Pontifical Gregorian University]] | [[University of Marburg]]}}\n| thesis_title       = \n| thesis_url         = \n| thesis_year        = \n| school_tradition   = \n| doctoral_advisor   = \n| academic_advisors  = \n| influences         = <!--must be referenced from a third party source-->\n| era                = \n| discipline         = Theology\n| sub_discipline     = <!--academic discipline specialist area \u2013 e.g. Sub-atomic research, 20th Century Danish specialist, Pauline research, Arcadian and Ugaritic specialist-->\n| workplaces         = {{unbulleted list | [[Xavier University]] | [[Union Theological Seminary (New York City)|Union Theological Seminary]]}}\n| doctoral_students  = <!--only those with WP articles-->\n| notable_students   = <!--only those with WP articles-->\n| main_interests     = [[Religious pluralism]]\n| notable_works      = \n| notable_ideas      = \n| influenced         = <!--must be referenced from a third party source-->\n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n}}\n'''Paul Francis Knitter''' (born 1939) was the Paul Tillich Professor of Theology, World Religions and Culture at [[Union Theological Seminary (New York City)|Union Theological Seminary, New York City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.utsnyc.edu/Page.aspx?pid=381|title=Paul F. Knitter|publisher=Union Theological Seminary|accessdate=January 20, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100105141742/http://www.utsnyc.edu/Page.aspx?pid=381|archivedate=January 5, 2010}}</ref> He continues as the Emeritus Professor of Theology, World Religions and Culture.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://utsnyc.edu/academics/faculty/emeritus/ |title=Faculty Emeriti/ae|publisher=Union Theological Seminary|accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref> He was formerly Emeritus Professor of Theology at [[Xavier University]] in [[Cincinnati]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quaker.org/ftc/PaulKnitterBio.html|title=Paul F. Knitter Biographical Summary|publisher=Friends Theological College|accessdate=20 January 2010}}</ref> Since publishing his book, ''No Other Name?'' (1985), Knitter has been widely known for his [[religious pluralism]].  Along with his friend and colleague, the Protestant philosopher of religion [[John Hick]], Knitter came under criticism from Cardinal [[Joseph Ratzinger]], later known as Pope Benedict XVI.\n\nIn 1984 he was one of 97 theologians and religious persons who signed [[A Catholic Statement on Pluralism and Abortion]], calling for pluralism and discussion within the [[Catholic Church]] regarding the [[Catholic Church and abortion|church's position on abortion]].<ref name=\"Keller et al\">{{cite book |first1=Rosemary Skinner |last1=Keller |first2=Rosemary Radford |last2=Ruether |first3=Marie |last3=Cantlon |title=Encyclopedia of Women and Religion in North America |volume=3 |publisher=Indiana University Press |year=2006 |isbn=978-0-253-34688-9 |pages=1104\u20131106}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nKnitter was born on February 25, 1939, in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]. He holds a licentiate from the [[Pontifical Gregorian University]] in Rome (1966), as well as a doctorate from the [[University of Marburg]], Germany (1972).\n\n==Works==\n===Thesis===\n*{{cite thesis |author1-last=Knitter |author1-first=Paul F. |author1-mask= |title=Towards a Protestant Theology of Religions |series=Marburger Theologische Studien |volume=11 |type=PhD |location=Marburg |publisher=N.G. Elwert |date=1974 |ISBN=9783770804856 |OCLC=611481104 }}\n\n===Books===\n*{{cite book |author1-last=Knitter |author1-first=Paul F. |author1-mask=3 |title=No Other Name? A Critical Survey of Christian Attitudes toward World Religions |series=American Society of Missiology series |volume=7 |location=Maryknoll, NY |publisher=Orbis Books |date=1985 |ISBN=9780883443477 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/noothernamecriti00knit }}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Knitter |editor1-first=Paul F. |editor1-mask=3 |editor2-last=Hick |editor2-first=John |editor2-link=John Hick |title=The Myth of Christian Uniqueness: Toward a Pluralistic Theology of Religions |url=https://archive.org/details/mythofchristianu00hick |url-access=registration |location=Maryknoll, NY |publisher=Orbis Books |date=1987 }}\n*{{cite book |author1-last=Knitter |author1-first=Paul F. |author1-mask=3 |author2-last=Hill |author2-first=Brennan |author2-link=Brennan Hill |author3-last=Madges |author3-first=William |author3-link=William Madges |title=Faith, Religion, and Theology: A Contemporary Introduction |location= |publisher=Twenty-Third Publications |date= 1989 }}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Knitter |editor1-first=Paul F. |editor1-mask=3 |editor2-last=Corless |editor2-first=Roger |editor2-link=Roger Corless |title=Buddhist Emptiness and Christian Trinity Essays and Explorations |location=Mahwah, NJ |publisher=Paulist Press |date=1990 |ISBN=9780809131310 }}\n*{{cite book |author1-last=Knitter |author1-first=Paul F. |author1-mask=3 |author2-last=Cobb, Jr. |author2-first=John B. |author2-link=John B. Cobb, Jr. |author3-last=Hellwig |author3-first=Monika |author3-link=Monika Hellwig |author4-last=Swidler |author4-first=Leonard |author4-link=Leonard Swidler |title=Death or Dialogue: From the Age of Monologue to the Age of Dialogue |location=London |publisher=SCM Press |date=1990 |ISBN=9780334024453 }}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Knitter |editor1-first=Paul F. |editor1-mask=3 |title=Pluralism and Oppression: Theology in World Perspective |series=Annual publication of the College Theology Society |volume=34 |location=Lanham |publisher=University Press of America |date=1990 |ISBN=9780819179043 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/pluralismoppress0000pani }}\n*{{cite book |author1-last=Knitter |author1-first=Paul F. |author1-mask=3 |title=One Earth Many Religions: Multifaith Dialogue and Global Responsibility |location=Maryknoll, NY |publisher=Orbis Books |date=1995 |ISBN=9781570750373 }}\n*{{cite book |author1-last=Knitter |author1-first=Paul F. |author1-mask=3 |title=Jesus and the Other Names: Christian Mission and Global Responsibility |location=Maryknoll, NY |publisher=Orbis Books |date=1996 |ISBN=9781570750533 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/jesusothernamesc0000knit }}\n*{{cite book |author1-last=Knitter |author1-first=Paul F. |author1-mask=3 |editor1-last=Swidler |editor1-first=Leonard |editor1-link=Leonard Swidler |editor2-last=Mojzes |editor2-first=Paul |editor2-link=Paul Mojzes |title=The Uniqueness of Jesus: A Dialogue with Paul Knitter |location=Maryknoll, NY |publisher=Orbis Books |date=1997 |ISBN=9781570751233 }}\n*{{cite book |author1-last=Knitter |author1-first=Paul F. |author1-mask=3 |title=Introducing Theologies of Religions |location=Maryknoll, NY |publisher=Orbis Books |date=2002 |ISBN=9781570754197 }}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Knitter |editor1-first=Paul F. |editor1-mask=3 |editor2-last=Muzaffar |editor2-first=Chandra |editor2-link=Chandra Muzaffar |title=Subverting Greed: Religious Perspectives on the Global Economy |location=Maryknoll, NY |publisher=Orbis Books |date=2002 |ISBN=9781570754463 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/subvertinggreedr2002unse }}\n*{{cite book |author1-last=Knitter |author1-first=Paul F. |author1-mask=3 |title=The Myth of Religious Superiority: multifaith explorations of religious pluralism |location=Maryknoll, NY |publisher=Orbis Books |date=2005 |ISBN=9781570756276 }}\n*{{cite book |author1-last=Knitter |author1-first=Paul F. |author1-mask=3 |title=Without Buddha I Could Not Be a Christian |location=Oxford |publisher=Oneworld |date=2009 |ISBN=9781851686735 }}\n\n===Critiques from within Paul Knitter's native Catholic tradition===\nIn reference to Paul Knitter's ''Jesus and the Other Names'' (Maryknoll, N.Y.: Orbis, 1996), [[Catherine Cornille]], when addressing Knitter's claim that Jesus is not the \"only\" savior, comments: \"Not only are the religious views of different traditions at times directly opposed or mutually exclusive, but the very claim of ultimacy of one religion necessarily precludes the truth of the claims of others.\"<ref>Catherine Cornille, ''The im-Possibility of Interreligious Dialogue'', New York, NY: Crossroad Publishing, 2008, p.87.</ref> \n\nIn reference to Knitter's ''Without Buddha I Could Not Be a Christian'' (Oxford: Oneworld Publications, 2009), [Rev.] James L. Fredericks declares: \"Nowhere are we given to believe that there are some respects in which Buddhists and Christians are simply baffling to one another because their religious visions are incompatible. I also worry that the more Buddhism is enlisted into service of Christian faith as an ''ancilla theologiae'' [handmaid to theology], the less it seems like Buddhism.\"<ref>J. Fredericks' pertaining review entitled \"The Lotus Position\", ''Commonweal Magazine'', April 5th, 2010.</ref>\n\nIn reference to ''Without Buddha I Could Not Be a Christian'', [[Robert Magliola]] asserts, in the ''Journal of the American Academy of Religion'' (''JAAR'')<ref>R. Magliola's pertaining review in ''JAAR'', Vol. 78, No. 4 (Dec., 2010), pp. 1215-1218.</ref> that Paul Knitter \"is not Catholic enough because he is not Buddhist enough and vice versa.\" Quoting [Rev.] Francis X. Clooney, S.J.'s assertion, in Clooney's ''Jesuit Postmodern'' (2006, p. 165) that comparisons \"seem not to fit into a single, coherent view,\" Magliola points out that Knitter's proposed \"one universal Spirit\" perpetuates the outdated modernist notion of \"equable holism\" or \"openness\" (the \"modern idol\") rather than the \"jagged, asymmetrical\" nature of reality.<ref>P. 1218.</ref>   \n\n\n\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Religion}}\n* [[Wilfred Cantwell Smith]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Union Theological Seminary (New York City)}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knitter, Paul F.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ponti